<TITLE> Popular Madrid mayor snubbed by opposition </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MADRID, Jan 16 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Spain's conservative opposition has excluded from its list of candidates for a March parliamentary election the popular mayor of Madrid, seen by some analysts as a potential magnet for swing voters. Spanish media said Mayor Alberto Ruiz-Gallardon would quit politics after the snub to his parliamentary ambitions, announced in a brief Popular Party communique late on Tuesday. The telegenic, socially liberal Gallardon was seen by political analysts as one of the PP's best hopes with swing voters who could be key in helping the party overcome the Socialist government's lead of 2-4 points in opinion polls. But Gallardon, who once presided over a gay marriage between a male PP official and his partner, was unpopular with the more conservative wing which has come to dominate the party. His status as a potential leadership candidate if the PP lost the electios also made him a threat to other top party membe
